isi

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict isi with group and time_point (formula: isi ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.46) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.17. The model’s intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 13.00 (S.E. = 2.05, p < .001, 95% CI [8.98, 17.02]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -3.00, S.E. = 2.90, p = 0.301, 95% CI [-8.69, 2.69]; Std. beta = -1.20, 95% CI [-3.47, 1.07])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -3.50, S.E. = 2.33, p = 0.133, 95% CI [-8.06, 1.06]; Std. beta = -1.40, 95% CI [-3.22, 0.42])
  • The effect of time point [3rd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -1.00, S.E. = 2.33, p = 0.667, 95% CI [-5.56, 3.56]; Std. beta = -0.40, 95% CI [-2.22, 1.42])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 3.50, S.E. = 3.29, p = 0.288, 95% CI [-2.95, 9.95]; Std. beta = 1.40, 95% CI [-1.18, 3.98])
  • The interaction effect of time point [3rd] on group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 2.00, S.E. = 3.29, p = 0.543, 95% CI [-4.45, 8.45]; Std. beta = 0.80, 95% CI [-1.78, 3.38])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
